04241nam a22005175i 9780226767352DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102006ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802267673527 a10.7208/97802267673522doi  a(DE-B1597)523758  a(OCoLC)747946401  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aB1607b.S69 2014 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a1922231 aSnyder, Laura J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReforming Philosophy :bA Victorian Debate on Science and Society /cLaura J. Snyder. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2010] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (386 p.) :b8 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue -- tIntroduction: “Reforming the Philosophy of the Age” -- t1. Whewell and the Reform of Inductive Philosophy -- t2. Mill’s Radicalization of Induction -- t3. Reforming Science -- t4. Reforming Culture: Morality and Politics -- t5. Reforming Political Economy -- tConclusion: The Debate’s Legacy -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Victorian period in Britain was an “age of reform.” It is therefore not surprising that two of the era’s most eminent intellects described themselves as reformers. Both William Whewell and John Stuart Mill believed that by reforming philosophy—including the philosophy of science—they could effect social and political change. But their divergent visions of this societal transformation led to a sustained and spirited controversy that covered morality, politics, science, and economics. Situating their debate within the larger context of Victorian society and its concerns, Reforming Philosophy shows how two very different men captured the intellectual spirit of the day and engaged the attention of other scientists and philosophers, including the young Charles Darwin. Mill—philosopher, political economist, and Parliamentarian—remains a canonical author of Anglo-American philosophy, while Whewell—Anglican cleric, scientist, and educator—is now often overlooked, though in his day he was renowned as an authority on science. Placing their teachings in their proper intellectual, cultural, and argumentative spheres, Laura Snyder revises the standard views of these two important Victorian figures, showing that both men’s concerns remain relevant today. A philosophically and historically sensitive account of the engagement of the major protagonists of Victorian British philosophy, Reforming Philosophy is the first book-length examination of the dispute between Mill and Whewell in its entirety. A rich and nuanced understanding of the intellectual spirit of Victorian Britain, it will be welcomed by philosophers and historians of science, scholars of Victorian studies, and students of the history of philosophy and political economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPhilosophy, Englishy19th century. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophyxHistoryy19th century. 0aSciencexPhilosophyxHistoryy19th century. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226767352423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226767352.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles